25|$|Before {{discussing}} Petty's economic theories, it {{is important}} to point out two crucial influences in his life. The first is Thomas <b>Hobbes,</b> for whom Petty acted as personal secretary. According to <b>Hobbes,</b> theory should set out the rational requirements for 'civil peace and material plenty'. As <b>Hobbes</b> had centred on peace, Petty chose prosperity.|$|E
25|$|Leviathan and the Air-Pump: <b>Hobbes,</b> Boyle, and the Experimental Life (published 1985) {{is a book}} by Steven Shapin and Simon Schaffer. It {{examines}} the debate between Robert Boyle and Thomas <b>Hobbes</b> over Boyle's air-pump experiments in the 1660s. In 2005, Shapin and Schaffer were awarded the Erasmus Prize for this work.|$|E
